segments.text: the same time there's more research and so the aim is switch that way.

Yes I think I think a lot of our students are prepared more particularly since they put in more math and you have a stronger pre-vet requirements and that calculus and I think I've had several graduate courses calculus I just learned to make a
summation sign and wrote in memory as far as I was concerned.
I checked out a book, Calculus Made Easy, but it didn't look too easy.
I always liked math, but that's one reason I advise some of the top students to take math.
Well, there's one in Florida now and has a PhD and he's doing research work in toxicology when he was a senior.
R.A.
Junior, I advised him to take calculus, and he took, made two A's.
And in the two, I think it was 201, 202 then, made A's in both semesters of calculus.
He loved that math.
But now it's a requirement.
As far as the students are concerned,
Back when you started vet school, there were just a handful of students that applied.
Now there's 600 a year that are applying to try to get into A&M vet school.
How can you count for this tremendous increase in applications?
Why is there so much interest?
I don't know.
One thing amazed me, why the interest in the women?
I never would have thought that women would have become so interested in it.
Some of them were quite successful.
Well, that leads to another thing.
In 1963, the very first woman was admitted to the vet school.
She was a good one, too.
Yeah.
Now, one-third of the student body over there is women.
A lot of faculty members are women.
Let's talk about the women in the vet school.
How did this come about?
Why did they admit her?
I don't know exactly why they admitted them, because they had applications.
Dean French came here from, I think he was in the chemistry department at VPI, Virginia Polytechnic.
And he was the dean of the graduate school here, and
recommended, oh, we had some splendid students from Virginia who came here in veterinary medicine.
And when he got his influence, when he had been here for several years, we could see that the quality dropped because he screened them.
And I'd say of all the Virginia students we had, I had only one mediocre to poor student.
He had a hard time getting a C.
But after that, well, we didn't have any more Virginia students.
And I think Dean French's attitude, he left here and went to Washington State and straightened out that institution.
I don't know.
He's probably retired now.
But he, I think, helped us.
He criticized us.
of not looking on ourselves as a graduate school, a professional school.
And he even thought that perhaps we should have, be governed by a different formula for evaluation for appropriations.
And I think he helped our morale a lot.
And not the dean, probably the dean,
got him to talk to us for that reason.
I don't recall which dean it was at the time.
I think the student is much better qualified now and to go into more things.
And I think that's one reason that these better students are screened to get in.
Some of them have master's degrees.
Some of them have PhD degrees.
Well, what about the women, though?
Well, there are more openings for veterinary medicine now, particularly, say, in the case of medical school.
You usually have somebody who has to take care of the animal colony, and frequently they'll have a veterinarian on the staff at the medical school.
who used to be in pathology, and I think he was an Oklahoma product, but he went from here to the Philippines, I think, then came back.
He's on the staff of the medical school in San Antonio University, Texas Medical School, but he's a veterinarian.
But we've had some capable women, too, and they have gotten into
The man has more opportunities, I think, in so far as going to things.
When women came, when women started back in 63, did you notice any, was there any resistance not to let women in, or was there any problems with the women?
Do you remember anything like that?
Or were they generally accepted right away?
I would like to think that there were isolated cases.
I know when Sonia came in in 63.
What was her last name?
Oliphant, O-L-I-P-H-A-N-T. She was from a small town between San Antonio and the border, or between San Antonio and Edinburgh, somewhere in there.
But she was interested in large animals, horses, and I remember one truck came in with some
a cow and a calf.

And there's some great big old boys in that class, and Sonia's a small person, I guess, I don't know, Sonia was about five, five, something like this, and weighed about 145 or 150, and she went in there and picked that calf out, put him in her arms, and knew what to do with it.
And there was an old boy standing around, you know, and she just went in there.
I had never heard of any adverse criticism of that girl because she was good all around.
Some of the girls that I had were rather mediocre.
Sonya was good.
And then I happened to hit two or three mediocre ones, and I'd find a real good one.
What do you think their overall quality was compared to the men?
Oh, it's much better now than back in those days.
But I mean, generally, are they about the same quality as the male students back in the mid-'60s?
I'd say this insofar as the last class I taught in 67, I think I had three or five, I don't recall.
I would say offhand that the average male was better than the average woman.
I wouldn't say they weren't misfits, but those girls had a pretty hard time, some of them.
And some of the students that perhaps didn't like them and made life pretty miserable.
But they had to get it the hard way.
I think that would be true almost anything.
And probably other classes too on the campus.
I recall when Mr.
Rudder was in Washington, when they decided to take in one summer school, to open it up to the female.
I guess that was probably in, when did they open up to the entire school?
I was within 63, but they didn't allow women in general.
That was at a veterinary school.
In the mid-60s, yeah.
Yeah, but when they did, Mr. Rutter was in Washington on business for the college, the university then.
And he complimented the, when he came back, he complimented the academic council on the way we handled taking in the women.
And...
The battalion was filled with editorials and with letters from students objecting to the girls.
Oh, my, they were fighting them.
They just didn't want to.
My oldest son, who's with the university now in executive development, when he heard it from me,
about the way we voted in academic council.
President Morgan had finished all the agenda for the day.
And someone, he says, anything else?
And someone said, how in order to protect women?
He said, well, he says, let's take a straw vote.
I said, I'd just like to.
I think there were 54 or 56 of us.
Every one of us held up a hand.
And I was home, and my oldest son told me, he said, how in the world could you vote for something like that?
Because he was an old laggy.
And that was, he was out through school.
He finished in 52.
He said, how in the world?
He was in the Air Force.
He says, how could you vote for something like that?
He says, what in the world will A&M come to?
And he had two classes, taught two classes, and had a bunch of girls in each one.
He didn't pay any attention to it now.
He just became a part of it.
But I think that's one of the best things that college ever did, was make it co-ed.
Sure.
In the vet school, what impact, in your opinion, was there an impact or were there any changes because they let women into the vet school?
Not that I know of.
Not that I know of.
I just knew of cases where they'd tell me that particular girls were having a pretty rough time with some of the students.
And most of the girls that they were talking about, they were mediocre students.
They weren't superiors to them.
But I never heard of one adverse criticism of Sonia.
She was a lady, a young lady, and she caused no trouble whatsoever that I ever knew of.
She was more interested in large animals, the boy she married.
He was about two, wasn't he?
But he was a grade later.
And she worked for the microbiology department for a year after she got her degree, until he got his degree.
He was interested in small animals, and she was interested in large animals.
But that's the way they were brought up.
Now, I have about two more final questions.
And one deals with why?
Can you tell me the story behind why you wrote the history?
Well, I wouldn't say it was pressure.
I had a chance to turn it down.
I did it first.
But I had just recently read Dr. Williams' history of Harry Long.
Oh, T. Harry Williams, yeah.
Yeah, of LSU.
And that's an excellent book.
That certainly is, isn't it?
And I got interested in how he had that documented.
He did a lot of oral histories.
T. Harry Williams did a lot of oral histories.
He did.
But I talked to the head of the department over here and he said, oh yes, he's a visiting lecturer.
He said he's an outstanding historian.
Yeah, unfortunately he died just recently, a few months ago, during the last year.
But I got interested in that and the way it was handled and when it was at McMurray's farewell party, I don't recall that year, exact year, but
We were in the veterinary library, and Dean Shelton walked up to me.
I always called him George.
I had him as a student.
And we got to talking, and then Wally Bay walked up.
And George says, we're interested in getting somebody to write a history of veterinary medicine.
said, what, do you have any recommendation?
I said, yes.
Al Price is a man you want.
And they laughed, both of them laughed, and I knew they were in cahoots.
So, they said, no, we want you to do it.
And I said, why not Al?
He said, well,
He's been on top of it, and he's afraid he couldn't treat it objectively.
I said, let me think about it.
And so I don't know whether I called him the next day or the second day or third day, and I finally told him I'd take it.
But I was happy that I did, because I got to visit with
Well, I visited every department, and Maurer helped me on the research part.
There were a lot of people that had to say so.
In fact, all of them read it, passed around, read it.
And they improved it.
Because I didn't touch all the bases, and I remember Al Price.
I didn't take it to Al.
I wish I had.
Because he looked at it, after it was all finished, he says, very good, but see, you didn't put everything in.
I said, goodness alive, who could?
I said, if there's anything left out, why in the world did you leave it out of your annual reports?
I said, I think I've touched pretty well all the bases in the annual reports.
But I had
It was passed back to me and said I had too much on the extension.
And he says, try to condense that.
And I said, well, about a half or a third.
I condensed it down to one third and saved some space.
But I enjoyed doing it.
And then one thing that I decided
After I found out there were so many PhDs and so many masters in there, Dean Shelton's request was that he'd like a list of all the PhDs.
I said, well, why not the masters?
He says, well, he says, if you ought to do it.
So then Doug goes up.
And the main thing, before I got through, I don't know whether I thought I had spoken out of turn.
Because one individual was listed in three, having received a master's degree in three departments.
They cleaned him.
And I knew what department had him.
And it turned out that physiology.
I knew he had taken physiology.
But two other departments had him.
So I finally went to him and asked him.
And he told me what it was in.
And what happened was that the secretaries, I asked each head of the department, they went through and these theses, dissertations, were all filed in that.
And they could have several copies made.
And so these other two departments had a copy of that thesis.
And that's the way it happened.
But I had to watch that, and I thought, I was afraid that I'd leave somebody out.
So I went to the graduate office and went through that file to see, get a check, but I didn't pick up any.
But I said, if I make one of commission,
It wouldn't be so bad, but I said, if I only met one person, I'm going to catch it.
And I should.
But one of the first ones I handed, handed one of these out.
He says, I found an arrow.
And I said, what's the problem more?
He said, I don't have a bachelor's degree.
I said, doggone it, you better be listed in there somewhere.
I said, that's either in one of the catalogs, the A&M Journal catalog.
I said, that's not of my thinking.
In fact, he's in the physiology department right now.
But he said, he got his DVM.
a master's and his PhD at Iowa State.
And never had a bachelor's degree.
And no bachelor's.
And so he said, I don't know.
I said, well, suppose you did have one and you had left it out.
I said, that's what had hurt me.
I said, well, it didn't hurt me having that thing on me.
And I said, I didn't put anybody's degree in there unless I found it listed somewhere, even in the general catalog.
are in the departments.
And I said, I've checked and double-checked that.
And I said, to me, that's a minor part.
And he laughed about it.
I have one final question, and that concerns your career at A&M.
How would you analyze or how would you summarize your career at A&M?
A happy experience.
A happy experience.
If I had to do it over again, I'd probably make the same mistakes.
I'd hope that I wouldn't, but...
Were there some major mistakes that you thought that you made?
Not that I know of, but... How about accomplishments?
Well, I know I came to the crossroads of, in the...
Oh, in the thirties, I think, as to whether I would concentrate and get all this work together.
The early thirties, in fact, is when it happened.
And get a Ph.D. or go on and take these specialized courses.
I did one course in the top physiologists of the country, and that was in his department.
A.J.
Carlson's Department of Physiology at the University of Chicago, and I wanted some work on one of the top physiological chemistry departments, and that was at the University of Chicago.
And the Kochs, Dr. and Mrs. Koch, both were in the department.
They were both in Europe that summer, but I got the work on Gustafson, who later was chancellor at Nebraska, and then later was
went with the Ford Company, Ford Foundation, and was considered as the president when Tom Harrington was made president here.
And his name is, I said, is that R.A.G.
of Colorado and University of Chicago fans?
He said, yes.
And I said, he's the top man.
I said, that's the best teacher, one of the best teachers I've ever had.
I said, he made chemistry look very easy to me.
And I said, I didn't tell them, but one of the best exams I ever stood, I think, was on that course under him, because he was par excellence as an instructor.
But they say he was too old.
I happened to be on the committee, the president's committee, for the selection of the president.
And I think he was 54 at the time we met him.

I think there was one representative from each one of the schools, and Gib Giltrus was chancellor, and Fred Jensen was chemistry, and I don't recall, Godbey was in agriculture, I don't recall the others.
So you took these short courses then?
Yes, and as some of them said, I know there was an endocrinologist here, not an endocrinologist, but, I can't dispel now, but he said,
you're making a mistake, says, you're going, what if you get fired one of these days?
I said, well, I'll go back to my first love and this practice.
And I says, I'm not worried about that.
He says, if I'm not good enough for the teacher here, why?
I don't care.
So I said, I think at the time, I'd be doing that.
But if I had to go over again, I might.
As things have developed, I might concentrate and
and work on a PhD.
But at the time I thought I did the best, better of the two because I wasn't degree-minded at the time.
And you think it was the best choice for you in the long run?
Yes.
I wouldn't take anything for that experience with Dr. Pymal.
Did you ever think about leaving A&M?
Did you ever think of another alternative, another university?
No, when I retired in 67, I had a chance of going to Iowa State for a year, but that was because their man in Farmer College came here.
I had nothing to do with thinking this, because I was a very good friend of the head of the department up there, and by his own choice, he had written down here something.
He wanted to come to Texas for some reason, and so we ended up having their
pharmacology instructor.
So I was going to fill in for a year and I turned it down.
I said no, I'd rather not.
So I was ready for a rest.
Well thanks, thank you very much for this interview.
Is there anything that you think we should talk about that I missed?
No, I think perhaps I've mentioned some things I shouldn't.
Then you can edit them out.
Thank you very much.
